Sentō Revival Project in Aichi – Understanding What Factors Drive Success in Public Bathhouses¶

Project Background & Purpose¶

Sent-themed restaurants in Aichi face growing challenges due to aging infrastructure, changing lifestyles, and limited budgets. While a few stylish locations in Tokyo have succeeded through design and social media, most rely on traditional features and loyal customers.

This project explores what truly drives success for these venues not through costly renovations, but by analyzing factors like location, pricing, operating hours, and customer feedback. The goal is to identify realistic strategies to help them thrive in aging communities with limited resources.

  • pandas and numpy for data handling,
  • matplotlib and seaborn for visualization,

  • sklearn modules for scaling and Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

Then load the Aichi Sento-Themed Restaurant Dataset using pandas.read_csv() and preview the first five rows to understand the structure and format of the data.

This step sets the foundation for all further data exploration, cleaning, and analysis.

Step 7: Multiple Linear Regression with Selected Features¶

Using the variables that showed the strongest correlation with monthly_visitors, we build a multiple linear regression model. The selected features include price, review count, population density, and opening hours.

After adding an intercept term, we fit the model using statsmodels.OLS() and review the summary output to evaluate the impact and significance of each predictor.

In [33]:
# Remove leading/trailing spaces in column names
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()


# Select your variables for Multiple Linear Regreession 
selected_features = [
    'average_price_for_use_yen',
    'google_review_count',
    'district_density',
    'open_hours_per_day'
]

# Define independent (X) and dependent (y) variables
X = df[selected_features]
y = df['monthly_visitors']

# Add a constant 
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Fit the model
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

print(model.summary())

Step 8: Interpretation of Regression Results¶

The regression model explains the success of sent-themed bathhouses through four key predictors, with a very strong R-squared of 0.919, meaning over 91% of the variation in monthly visitors is explained by this model.

Key Findings:¶

  • Price is Critical:
    average_price_for_use_yen has a strong negative coefficient (-1.1013, p < 0.001). This means that as the average price increases by 1 yen, the number of visitors decreases by about 1 person per month. This confirms that affordable pricing is essential for attracting more customers, especially when the bathhouse isn't trendy.

  • Google Reviews Drive Visibility:
    google_review_count has a strong positive effect (+1.1064, p < 0.001). Every additional review is associated with approximately one more monthly visitor, showing that online presence and customer engagement significantly influence success.

  • Location Matters:
    district_density also has a positive impact (+0.0738, p < 0.001). Bathhouses located in more populated areas naturally draw more traffic, suggesting that targeting higher-density districts can lead to better performance.

  • Longer Hours Increase Foot Traffic:
    open_hours_per_day has a positive coefficient (+19.67, p < 0.001), meaning that for each additional hour of operation per day, the bathhouse gains nearly 20 more monthly visitors. This shows the importance of flexible, extended hours in serving diverse customer schedules.

Conclusion:¶

Even without trendy branding or expensive redesigns, sent-style bathhouses can succeed by focusing on:

  • Lower pricing
  • Strong online presence
  • Strategic urban locations
  • Longer operating hours

These factors directly and measurably increase visitor numbers, making them critical levers for sustainable growth.

Step 9: Principal Component Regression (PCR)¶

To reduce dimensionality and address potential multicollinearity among correlated predictors, we apply Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to a selected group of independent variables. These include pricing, online reputation, location density, operating hours, and several binary features.

Why PCA?¶

  • PCA transforms the original correlated variables into a smaller set of uncorrelated principal components.
  • This allows us to simplify the model while still capturing most of the original datas variance.
  • Its especially useful when working with many features that may interact or overlap in meaning (e.g., discount types, amenities, and accessibility).

How PCR Compares to Simple Multiple Regression:¶

Aspect Multiple Linear Regression Principal Component Regression
Variables Uses original features Uses transformed components
Interpretability High direct variable impact Lower abstract combinations
Risk of multicollinearity Possible if variables are correlated Avoided by construction
Dimensionality Can increase with more features Reduced by selecting fewer components

Trade-offs:¶

  • PCR improves model stability and handles correlation well, but the components themselves are less interpretable.
  • Unlike simple regression, you cant say exactly how much each original variable influences the target only how the grouped components do.

This step gives us a robust, cleaner model to validate the trends found in the earlier regression and better generalize our findings.

Step 10: Interpretation of Principal Component Regression (PCR) Results¶

The PCR model uses three principal components (PC1, PC2, PC3) derived from nine original features. It explains 43.3% of the variance in monthly visitors (R = 0.433), which is moderate and significantly lower than the simple regression model (R = 0.919). However, the model is still statistically significant (p < 0.001) and avoids multicollinearity.

Coefficient Insights:¶

  • PC1 (Positive, +256.2):
    This component has the strongest positive effect on visitor numbers. It likely represents a combination of high review count, urban density, and longer opening hours all business-performance enhancers.

  • PC2 (Positive, +120.3):
    Also positively related to monthly visitors, but less strongly than PC1. It may include features like customer-friendly amenities or discount programs.

  • PC3 (Negative, -93.95):
    This component negatively affects visitor numbers. It could be associated with less favorable traits, such as higher pricing or operational restrictions.

All components are statistically significant (p < 0.001), showing they meaningfully contribute to predicting success, though less precisely than individual variables in the earlier model.

Final Takeaway:¶

  • While PCR helps simplify the model and avoid multicollinearity, it sacrifices interpretability we can't directly say which exact features cause the changes in visitor numbers.
  • The original regression model remains more powerful for interpretation and decision-making, but PCR supports and validates the broader trends.

Step 11: Interpretation of PCA Loadings¶

To understand the meaning of each principal component (PC), we examine the loadings, which show how strongly each original variable contributes to each component.

🔹 PC1 — "Operational Value & Accessibility"¶

This component is most strongly influenced by:

  • Positively: is_24_hour_open (0.44), has_senior_discount (0.42), district_density (0.39), has_student_discount (0.20)
  • Negatively: average_price_for_use_yen (-0.47), open_hours_per_day (-0.43)

Interpretation: PC1 represents value-driven and accessible operations. It favors venues with discounts, full-day access, and locations in dense areas, while penalizing high prices and limited hours.

🔹 PC2 — "Digital Reputation & Experience Features"¶

Strongly loaded by:

  • google_rating (0.54)
  • district_density and google_review_count (both 0.49)
  • has_sauna (0.24)

Interpretation: PC2 captures online reputation and wellness features. High values in this component reflect places that are digitally well-rated, reviewed, and offer relaxing amenities.

🔹 PC3 — "Amenity-Specific Factors"¶

  • Positively: has_sauna (0.61), has_student_discount (0.28)
  • Negatively: has_senior_discount (-0.42), open_hours_per_day (-0.41), google_review_count (-0.37)

Interpretation: PC3 reflects amenity trade-offs such as promoting saunas or student perks, while associating less with senior support, longer hours, and review count. It may signal a different niche or visitor demographic.

Why This Matters:¶

Understanding loadings helps decode the PCA regression results. For example:

  • PC1 had the strongest positive effect on visitor numbers so features like 24-hour access, discounts, and dense locations are powerful drivers.
  • PC3 had a negative effect, suggesting that amenities like saunas or student discounts alone may not guarantee higher traffic without broader appeal or accessibility.

These insights refine our understanding of what clusters of features drive sent-style bathhouses success, even in the absence of trendy branding.

Final Recommendations for Sentō Bathhouses¶

Realistic Improvements (Low-Cost Strategies)¶

Based on the analysis, traditional sent bathhouses can increase customer traffic without expensive redesigns by focusing on the following:

  • Keep prices affordable: Lower pricing is strongly linked with higher visitor numbers. Offering value-based pricing can attract more local customers.
  • Encourage Google reviews: Actively ask satisfied customers to leave reviews. This boosts visibility and credibility at no cost.
  • Extend operating hours: Longer hours are associated with more visitors. Even small extensions (e.g., opening 1 hour earlier) can lead to measurable gains.
  • Target high-density areas: If opening a new location, choose districts with higher residential populations to maximize walk-in potential.
  • Offer basic discounts: Simple loyalty programs or senior/student discounts add perceived value and drive repeat visits.

🔍 Suggested Additional Data Sources¶

To further improve the analysis and model accuracy, the following data would be valuable:

  • Customer demographics: Age, gender, and household type could help segment customer behavior.
  • Competitor data: Locations, prices, and online ratings of nearby bathhouses or wellness centers for benchmarking.
  • Monthly revenue: In addition to visitors, revenue figures would allow profitability analysis.
  • Marketing efforts: Social media spend, promotions, or local partnerships could reveal drivers beyond location and amenities.
  • Customer satisfaction surveys: Direct feedback on service quality, cleanliness, and atmosphere.

Collecting this information would allow for more personalized, data-driven strategies that support sustainable business growth even under tight budgets.
